To locate where a segmentation fault occurs:

E.g:
Process 12299 (ipc_test) terminated SIGSEGV code=1 fltno=11 ip=fe36d094 mapaddr=
00005094. ref=00000064

From the error message, get the ip.  Then use gdb-qnx to locate the problem
from the executable:

gdb-qnx <prog>
l *0x<ip>

If the ip is actually in one of the shared objects, then we need to first
locate which shared object the ip is within:

pidin -p<prog> mem

E.g.:
# pidin -pipc_test mem
     pid tid name               prio STATE           code  data         stack
   57352   1 proc/boot/ipc_test  10r JOIN             8192  452K  8192(516K)*
   57352   2 proc/boot/ipc_test  10f RECEIVE          8192  452K  4096(132K) 
   57352   3 proc/boot/ipc_test   9f CONDVAR          8192  452K  4096(132K) 
   57352   4 proc/boot/ipc_test   8f RECEIVE          8192  452K  4096(132K) 
            ldqnx.so.2         @fe300000             376K   40K
            ipc_lib.so         @fe368000              32K   12K

From the memory map, identify the shared object.
Then use the gdb with the shared object, and use the mapaddr
to locate the error.

gdb-qnx <lib.so>
l *0x<mapaddr>


----------------------------------

Here is how you get the stack address:

#include <sys/syspage.h>

    uint32 stackaddr;
    extern struct cpupage_entry *_cpupage_ptr;
                                     // Note: a hidden object known by linker

    stackaddr = (uint32)_cpupage_ptr->tls->stackaddr;

